1. Core Backend Architecture
A standard school management backend is often built using a RESTful API architecture

Models/Schemas: Defines data structures like Student (name, email, roll number), Teacher (specialization, schedule), and Course.
Controllers: Logic for handling requests like "Enroll a student" or "Post grades".
Authentication: Role-based access control (RBAC) to ensure a student cannot change their own grades. 

2. Implementation Examples by Language
Depending on your tech stack, you can find full-source code on GitHub: 
Node.js (MERN Stack): A popular choice using Express and MongoDB. You can find comprehensive implementations like the MERN-School-Management-System which includes specific logic for admin-teacher-student roles.
PHP (Laravel): For a structured MVC approach, the Laravel School Management Backend provides pre-built migrations and seeders for school databases.
Java: For enterprise-grade systems, tutorials on TechVidvan walk through building a student management system using Java and SQLite. 

3. Essential Database Schema
A basic Back4app School Schema should include these relational tables: 
Users: ID, Name, Email, Password (hashed), Role (Admin/Teacher/Student).
Classroom: ID, Subject, TeacherID, RoomNumber.
Enrollments: StudentID, ClassroomID, Grade, AttendanceCount. 
